Habitat description. The source of the Tzaconejá River is in the western mountains in central Chiapas. The river travels southeastward along the Lacantún Basin to drain into the Lacantún River, close to the border with Guatemala . At the type locality the river channel is wide (ca. 20–30 m ) with limestone cobble and bedrock (
Fig. 6
). The collecting was conducted in riffles and in shallow areas with current by disturbing the substrate and holding the net downstream. This method was particularly difficult at the type locality because mineral deposition had cemented cobbles to the bedrock.

Distribution. This species was collected from rivers in the highlands and western mountain regions of Chiapas state at elevations above 1000 meters, which are part of the Chiapas biogeographic province. We suspect this species also is present in streams of the western mountains of the Sierra Madre de Chiapas and the easternmost limit (Oaxaca) of the Sierra Madre del Sur biogeographic provinces. In Guatemala the species was collected in the central mountains of the Sierra de los Cochumatanes (
Fig. 4
).
